# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intervals are sorted.
There are intervals coming strictly before, after, and intersecting the new interval

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Partition the input intervals into three categories:
   - preceeding the new interval
   - intersecting the new interval, thus merged into one interval
   - following the new interval
2. Return these joined interval categories


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$, the space for the resulting intervals is not counted
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
## Python 3
```
class Solution:
    def insert(self, intervals: List[List[int]], newInterval: List[int]) -> List[List[int]]:
        start, end = newInterval
        prefix, suffix = [], []
        for i in intervals:
            if i[1] < start:
                prefix.append(i)
            elif i[0] > end:
                suffix.append(i)
            else:
                start, end = min(start, i[0]), max(end, i[1])
        return prefix + [[start, end]] + suffix
```
## JavaScript
```
/**
 * @param {number[][]} intervals
 * @param {number[]} newInterval
 * @return {number[][]}
 */
var insert = function(intervals, newInterval) {
    let [start, end] = newInterval;
    const [prefix, suffix] = [[], []];
    for (const i of intervals) {
        if (i[1] < start) {
            prefix.push(i);
        } else if (i[0] > end) {
            suffix.push(i);
        } else {
            start = Math.min(start, i[0]);
            end = Math.max(end, i[1]);
        }
    }
    return [...prefix, [start, end], ...suffix];
};
```

